        "description": {
            "name": "description",
            "type": "java.lang.String",
            "value": "Hi\n\nThe documentation for Zend_Rest_Server and _Client is a good start, but I had to spend a fair bit of time Googling, experimenting, and digging through the source to get it to work. A few changes to the docs might make it easier for others...?\n\nZend_Rest_Server example 45.6 could be shown as part of a normal Zend_Controller_Action, giving the complete context that you need to get a server working.  \n    function restAction()\n    {\n        $this->_helper->viewRenderer->setNoRender();\n        $server = new Zend_Rest_Server();\n        $server->setClass('My_Service_Class');\n        $server->handle( $this->_request->getParams() );\n    }        \n \nNote that My_Service_Class should do its own parameter validation in each public method.\n\n\nZend_Rest_Client example 45.1 is slightly misleading\n\nDifferences in Calling:\nIf you are calling a web service that is part of a standard Zend Framework application, you can't use the ->get() method because it appends ?method=sayHello&who=Davey&when=Day to the URL (eg resulting in http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/webservice\/rest\/?method=sayHello&who=Davey&when=Day), which doesn't work. You need to use ->post() instead so that the standard routers can correctly separate the parameters.\n\nIf your web service needs a session eg to maintain logged in status then call $client->getHTTPClient()->setCookieJar(); eg\n$client = new Zend_Rest_Client('http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/rest');\n$client->getHTTPClient()->setCookieJar();\n$client->login( $user, $password )->post(); \necho $client->sayHello('Davey', 'Day')->post();\n\n----\nThanks: have been very impressed with how easy this component is to use, and how well it is integrated with the rest of the framework. \n"
        },
